 1314","1309":"1309","Tyne River,Kent,England":"River, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Bampton, Devon, England":"Bampton, Devon, England","Connaught, Ireland":"Connaught, Ireland","Bampton, Tiverton, Devonshire, England":"Bampton, Devon, England","Bampton, Devon, England, Great Britain":"Bampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Bampton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Bampton, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cogan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Jewish (from Ukraine) <b>Kogan</b>, from the Russian pronunciation of   Cohen  .","Irish and Welsh (of Norman origin): habitational name from Cogan near Cardiff, which may have been named with a Welsh word meaning ‘bowl, depression’. In 1166 Milo de Cogan, held two fees near Penarth (Glamorganshire) of William earl of Gloucester. Members of this Norman family probably account for the name's appearance in 13th-century Berwickshire. By this time the family was also present in Ireland, associated with counties Limerick and Cork. It may have been the Irish branch that later brought the name to southwest Scotland.","Irish (Leitrim): variant of   Coogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cogen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Dorith.  German Erwin.","Variant of   Cogan  ."]},{"name":"Coggin","meanings":["English: variant of   Cogan  ."]},{"name":"Cohen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Meyer, Isadore, Emanuel, Moshe, Shlomo, Myer, Avi, Yehuda, Chaim.","Jewish: from Hebrew <i>kohen</i> ‘priest’. Priests are traditionally regarded as members of a hereditary caste descended from Aaron, brother of Moses. See also   Kaplan  .","Irish (Galway and Sligo): variant of   Coyne  ."]},{"name":"Coggins","meanings":["English: variant of   Cogan  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Coggan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Conal, Seamus.  Jewish Hyman.","English: variant of   Cogan  .","Americanized form of Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic) <b>Kogan</b>, from the Russian pronunciation of   Cohen  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":14,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Cogan was born in 1276, in Bampton, Devon, England, his father, John De Cogan, was 47 and his mother, Juliana Fitzgerald, was 37. He married Petronilla Parnell in 1298, in River, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 20 February 1314, in his hometown, at the age of 38, and was buried in Bampton, Devon, Engl